00:42.440 --> 00:50.220
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. Science Fiction Chronicle is a major science
fiction and fantasy news magazine distributed by Algal Press, which appears

00:50.220 --> 00:57.200
monthly. Its publisher is Andrew Porter, who for most of his life has been a
science fiction fan. Porter told us how he discovered science fiction. It's a

00:57.200 --> 01:06.060
story familiar to most of us. My brother was reading SF first. He's five years
older than I am. So when he was 15 and I was 10, I just started picking it up

01:06.060 --> 01:17.660
from him. And he still reads SF, but obviously I have gone much further, much
deeper into the subject than he would have ever dreamed of. Porter went on to

01:17.660 --> 01:24.880
produce several fan publications, then he started Algal Magazine. Algal was
later named Starship, which is still a viable magazine. Porter founded Algal

01:24.880 --> 01:32.280
Press when his ambitions grew. Science Fiction Chronicle is another one of the
productions of Algal Press. We asked him who else is involved in running Algal

01:32.280 --> 01:44.520
Press. When I started, wanted to start publishing chapbooks and books and stuff
like that, I adopted the name Algal Press from Algal Magazine. But it's not

01:44.520 --> 01:54.920
really a... It's just sort of like the name I press, and if I do chapbooks or
books or something... I mean, I did one book, really. I did the Book of Ellison,

01:55.420 --> 02:05.320
which is a real hardcover and a trade paperback. But people think it's... I work
for this vast Algal Press. And of course, also the appearance of Starship and

02:05.320 --> 02:13.340
Chronicle, like, wow, typeset. And Starship has, or at least had, four-color
covers. Wow, he's got this vast organization behind him. He's not a fan at all,

02:13.380 --> 02:16.540
they say. It's just all me, pasting stuff up in my living room.

02:25.860 --> 02:34.960
After having published several fanzines, Porter started Science Fiction
Chronicle. It was the magazine he had always dreamed of doing. So for years, I

02:34.960 --> 02:43.380
carried on my business card... You have a business card that impresses people
and costs five bucks or five thousand. And I had a thing called SF Chronicle

02:43.380 --> 02:52.540
listed in there, you know, which was just a title. And it was like the newsie I
always wanted to do. Finally, in 1979, I started as a news section in Ellgo,

02:54.300 --> 03:00.300
which at that time had become Starship by then, changed the title. More hardcore
SF title.

03:03.560 --> 03:15.380
And it started out with, you know, getting subscriptions. So in other words, I
actually started it with several hundred subscriptions. And it was just a thing

03:15.380 --> 03:23.720
done the way I wanted to do it, like typeset and nicely laid out, stuff like
that. Science Fiction Chronicle just had its fourth birthday. It's a rarity for

03:23.720 --> 03:32.260
a science fiction news magazine to have survived for so long. Through the years,
various people have started out news zines. And they've all folded. They've all

03:32.260 --> 03:39.800
gone away. They've all stopped publishing. And people got tired or they got
tired of losing money or something. And it didn't. It's still here. It's doing

03:39.800 --> 03:53.120
pretty well. I mean, it's not... I don't think it's making money yet. But it's
at the break-even point, which is always nice. Advertising is increasing. Now

03:53.120 --> 04:00.680
the recession is ending. Things are starting to take off. Why would a fan devote
his life to producing a news magazine such as Science Fiction Chronicle,

04:00.880 --> 04:08.840
especially since it doesn't net him much profit? Porter told us his reasons.
I've always loved science fiction. I mean, I could probably make a lot more

04:08.840 --> 04:19.800
money publishing a magazine with a lot of naked people in it. Or, you know, or
something, motorcycles or, you know, Hells Angels official newsletter or

04:19.800 --> 04:28.200
something like that. You know, if you don't buy this newsletter, it will kill
you. One of those things. I don't know. But I just love science fiction. I've

04:28.200 --> 04:35.780
always loved science fiction. And if I can make my living doing something in
science fiction, that's great. Porter also gets a kick out of producing Science

04:35.780 --> 04:44.880
Fiction Chronicle. The kick really is getting up when I feel like it and working
until when I feel like it and not having a boss to yell at me and say, you

04:44.880 --> 04:51.720
screwed up. Or I screwed up and you're going to take the blame because I'm your
boss. We'll have more on our next show with publisher Andrew Porter.

