This is Darrell Lane. And Bill Vernon. Algal Press is a one-man operation which
publishes the magazine Starship, an occasional book, and the monthly trade

06:35.780 --> 06:43.000
newspaper Science Fiction Chronicle. Andrew Porter of Brooklyn is the one-man
operator. He handles all aspects of the business, from subscriptions to

06:43.000 --> 06:51.200
advertising, from editorializing to arranging the printing. Recently we spoke
with Porter, and we asked him to describe a typical work day. I get up anywhere

06:51.200 --> 06:53.800
from about 10.30 to 11.30,

06:56.540 --> 07:01.540
and putter around, and I'll

07:01.540 --> 07:15.060
do stuff in the morning like entering financial stuff or getting checks ready
for deposit and, say, go into Midtown. And I hit a whole bunch of stuff in one

07:15.060 --> 07:26.860
stop on the subway. There's my commercial bank for my accounts, you know,
Starship and SF Chronicle and stuff. And then two doors away there's my personal

07:26.860 --> 07:37.120
savings bank. Across the street is the New York office of the printer I use. And
I can go in there and use their tie line to co-op the printer out in

07:37.120 --> 07:46.320
Pennsylvania and find out how stuff's doing. Or I can deliver stuff that has to
be, you know, they have a pouch system overnight. There's a stationery store

07:46.320 --> 07:57.920
near there I use, and my post office box is up there in Grand Central Station
and the place where I have pictures developed and all that. And, you know, then

07:57.920 --> 08:13.820
I come back home and I'll do other stuff at night. I like to work late at night,
very quiet. I have a TV going, some background noise. I watch Johnny

08:13.820 --> 08:24.440
Carson, and then David Letterman comes on. And then after that there's a very
good news program called News Overnight on NBC, which is very tongue-in-cheek.

08:24.640 --> 08:33.360
They do a lot, not ready for primetime news and other strange things. And then
if I'm really working straight through, there's two issues, two episodes of Mary

08:33.360 --> 08:43.160
Tyler Moore come on. It's followed by an episode of Bob Newhart. And by that
time, it's four in the morning, and then I love to see a rerun come on. Usually

08:43.160 --> 08:51.940
I can't stand that at all, so I just turn off my feet. Or I'll knock off the
door earlier and then read. The April 1983 issue of Science Fiction Chronicle

08:51.940 --> 09:00.720
had some startling headlines. Cherry, Spinred, to Wed, Collaborate. Dahl pays
$50 million for New American Library. The New England Science Fiction

09:00.720 --> 09:09.760
Association acquires Sheraton Boston. These turned out to be fictitious. They
were an April Fool's joke. Porter told us about it. I asked people's permission

09:09.760 --> 09:20.520
to do that. I asked Don Warren's permission to do that story. And I asked
Cherry's permission, and I asked Spinred's. And I arranged this sort of a

09:20.520 --> 09:29.340
matchmaker thing. I was saying, well, who would you like to get married to? And
Cherry didn't mind Spinred, and Spinred didn't mind Cherry. And I ran those

09:29.340 --> 09:37.740
stories. And a heck of a lot of people believe those stories. I understand that
various writers were calling other writers out and reading the issues over the

09:37.740 --> 09:46.680
phone and stuff. And people who knew Spinred knew he was planning to move out of
New York. If you slide down, you're going to move to Oklahoma, not Los Angeles.

09:50.760 --> 09:58.660
And if it's set in sight, people believe it. Porter promised there will be a
special treat to appear in the April of 1984 issue of Science Fiction Chronicle.

09:59.180 --> 10:08.880
For next April, I have two ideas I'm going to use. And this one was kind of
funny and humorous, like the thing with the New England Science Fiction

10:08.880 --> 10:10.840
Association buying a shirt in Boston.

10:14.120 --> 10:23.780
And I have two ideas I'm going to use. And one is going to be either, I won't
tell you what they are, the specific ideas, but one will either be kind of

10:23.780 --> 10:33.000
interesting and humorous, or the other might be horrifying, and I think will
scare the hell out of a lot of people. And it won't be humorous, but it's going

10:33.000 --> 10:40.720
to be possible. It's going to be a possible story, but it's going to scare a lot
of people, and I think it might anger a lot of people, too. But it'll be

10:40.720 --> 10:44.100
interesting. It'll be a hope. More with Andrew Porter on our next show.

