This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Ardeth Mayhar is an East Texas writer who
recently began publishing in a variety of genres. She has written several

24:27.420 --> 24:34.540
fantasy novels and one science fiction novel, that being a continuation of the
Fuzzy series started by the late H. Bean Piper. Mayhar's contribution to that

24:34.540 --> 24:41.800
series is entitled Golden Dream, a Fuzzy Odyssey. Mayhar has written some
westerns and she's working in other genres. She manages to write a lot because

24:41.800 --> 24:49.960
she works so rapidly. This is amazing because she lives on a farm and she has a
lot of chores to do each day. We asked Mayhar to describe a typical day. My

24:49.960 --> 25:00.060
husband and I get up at six. He has to go to town and open up his service day.
So I get up and fix breakfast for him at six. And at 8.15 comes the postman. So

25:00.060 --> 25:09.900
I'm standing there. I'm washing dishes or I'm out there milking the cow and I'm
listening for the postman. You know when Snoopy is a vulture, when he's on top

25:09.900 --> 25:13.740
of his doghouse being a vulture, that's the way I am with the postman.

25:16.500 --> 25:30.360
I milked one of the cows and turned the five calves in on her and her partner
and then feed the goats and feed the cats and feed the dogs. Then I get the mail

25:30.360 --> 25:43.380
and look through. And I get this interesting mail. A lot of days I begin my real
work. Of course, in among this, I usually try to sweep the porch and straighten

25:43.380 --> 25:52.500
the stacks. I've discovered you don't have to clean your living room if you keep
your stacks straight. So I straighten the stacks. Then I hit the typewriter

25:52.500 --> 26:06.360
about nine o'clock usually. And I may answer six letters before I start writing.
But then I will usually write, depending on what I am engaged in, from three to

26:06.360 --> 26:19.540
seven hours. I can write a pretty fair-sized short story in two and a half,
three hours. But if I'm working on a book and it's really hot, well, I'll go

26:19.540 --> 26:29.080
right on to it until 3.30 or 4 o'clock sometimes. And I'm one of these lucky
people. I don't have to eat. I don't need to eat. So I don't get hungry. I don't

26:29.080 --> 26:42.640
have to interrupt myself. And about 3.30 or 4, though, the goat starts yelling
out the pen. I don't know why she yells at 4 o'clock. But she usually does. And

26:42.640 --> 26:52.980
that wakes me up. And I think, you know, I don't know whether I can get my old
bones up from here or not. I'd better try and see, you know. Among much creaking

26:52.980 --> 27:07.680
and groaning, I point myself off the stool and straighten out and uncrink the
back. And so that's then when I go out and, oh, I may dig in my garden or take a

27:07.680 --> 27:19.980
walk up our little road. It's time to get back. It's time to lick the cat all
over again and milk the cows and put the calves on and feed the goats and all

27:19.980 --> 27:29.500
that good stuff. And then it's time to go supper for Papa. And he gets home
about 6.30. And so we're pretty well ready to pack it in.

27:37.140 --> 27:45.840
So Mayhar's farm chores take up a great deal of her day. We wondered if she
might be more productive if she were to live in the city. I am a peasant to my

27:45.840 --> 27:58.900
